<H2>Even More Word Q &amp; A</H2>
<P>This question came across my desk last week. </P>
<P>Can you add a section TOC in a Word document? </P>
<P>You have your main table of contents, or TOC, at the beginning of =
your=20
document=E2=80=94but what if you want to create a separate TOC in one of =
the sections or=20
chapters of your document? </P>
<P>For example, can you list your level 1 and level 2 headings in the =
main table=20
of contents at the beginning of the document and list your level 3 =
headings=20
inside the section of the document where they appear? </P>
<P><IMG alt=3D""=20
src=3D"http://stunna42.members.winisp.net/042908_1751_EvenMoreWor1.jpg"=20
mce_src=3D"http://stunna42.members.winisp.net/042908_1751_EvenMoreWor1.jp=
g"> </P>
<P>At this point, you may be thinking, "Of course you can. You just use =
field=20
codes." </P>
<P>That's true. However, building a TOC from scratch in the=20
<STRONG>Field</STRONG> dialog box can be daunting. And you don't have to =
do it=20
that way=E2=80=94at least, not all the way that way. </P>
<P>Instead, to build a table of contents, you can start with the =
<STRONG>Table=20
of Contents</STRONG> dialog box. </P>
<H1>Adding a separate section TOC in Word? </H1>
<P>First, create the table of contents that's going to go at the =
beginning of=20
the document. </P>
<P>(Remember to assign styles to the all headings that you want to =
appear in=20
your TOC.) </P>
<P>On the <STRONG>References</STRONG> tab, click <STRONG>Table of=20
Contents</STRONG>, and then click <STRONG>Insert Table of =
Contents</STRONG>. In=20
the dialog box, specify to show only two levels. </P>
<P><IMG alt=3D""=20
src=3D"http://stunna42.members.winisp.net/042908_1751_EvenMoreWor2.jpg"=20
mce_src=3D"http://stunna42.members.winisp.net/042908_1751_EvenMoreWor2.jp=
g"> </P>
<P>Click <STRONG>OK</STRONG>. </P>
<P>Now click where you want to insert the section TOC. </P>
<P>Click <STRONG>Table of Contents</STRONG> and <STRONG>Insert Table of=20
Contents</STRONG> again, and then click <STRONG>Options</STRONG>. In the =

<STRONG>Available styles</STRONG> list, delete the values for Heading 1 =
and=20
Heading 2, and then type <STRONG>3</STRONG> in the box for Heading 3. =
</P>
<P><IMG alt=3D""=20
src=3D"http://stunna42.members.winisp.net/042908_1751_EvenMoreWor3.jpg"=20
mce_src=3D"http://stunna42.members.winisp.net/042908_1751_EvenMoreWor3.jp=
g"> </P>
<P>Click <STRONG>OK</STRONG> twice=E2=80=94and when you're asked whether =
you want to=20
replace the existing TOC, click <STRONG>No</STRONG>. </P>
<H1>What if I want separate TOCs in more than one section? </H1>
<P>Good question! This takes a little more time, but it can be done. To =
add a=20
separate section TOC for each section or chapter, you need to use =
bookmarks.=20
Select all of the text, including the headings, that you want in the =
first=20
section TOC, and then on the <STRONG>Insert</STRONG> tab, click=20
<STRONG>Bookmark</STRONG>. </P>
<P>In the <STRONG>Bookmark</STRONG> dialog box, type a name, such as =
Chapter1,=20
click <STRONG>Add</STRONG>, and then click <STRONG>OK</STRONG>. </P>
<P><IMG alt=3D""=20
src=3D"http://stunna42.members.winisp.net/042908_1751_EvenMoreWor4.jpg"=20
mce_src=3D"http://stunna42.members.winisp.net/042908_1751_EvenMoreWor4.jp=
g"> </P>
<P>Create bookmarks for each section or chapter that will need a section =
TOC.=20
</P>
<P>After your bookmarks are in place, you can insert the section TOC the =
same=20
way that you did before. Just don't be alarmed when it shows every level =
3=20
heading in your document. We're going to fix that. </P>
<P>Click next to that section TOC, and then press ALT+F9. Your TOC is =
replaced=20
by a field code that probably looks something like this. </P>
<P><SPAN style=3D"BACKGROUND-COLOR: #bfbfbf"><STRONG>{</STRONG> TOC \o =
"3-3" \h \z=20
\u<STRONG>}</STRONG></SPAN> </P>
<P>All you need to do is type \b and the name of your bookmark, like =
this: </P>
<P><SPAN style=3D"BACKGROUND-COLOR: #bfbfbf"><STRONG>{</STRONG> TOC \o =
"3-3" \h \z=20
\u \b Chapter1<STRONG>}</STRONG></SPAN> </P>
<P>Press ALT+F9 again so that you can see the TOC. Press F9 to update =
it=E2=80=94and=20
when asked, click to update the whole table. </P>
<P>Getting the rest of your section TOCs into your document is easy. =
Press=20
ALT+F9 again to see the field code. Select it, press CTRL+C to copy it, =
and then=20
paste it in each place that you want to add a TOC, changing the name to =
the=20
correct bookmark name for that location. </P>
<P>After you paste and update the last section TOC, press ALT+F9 a final =
time,=20
so that you can see all of the section TOCs in your document. </P>
<P>Done! </P>
